text=:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Expansion: Two Considerations on Cochlear Implants%0a:Author: VikramM%0a:Original: [[Articles.CochlearImplants|CochlearImplants]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sathyas|sathyas]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 05.05.2021 - 22:02%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-184620-31780#%0a* [-06.05.2021 - 11:46-] || TA_audrey marked as complete%0a#foxend 210506-184620-31780#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhile researching for the linguistic discrimination in the wild category, I came across discussion of the bias in the medical field in favor of cochlear implants. In the discussion about discrimination in medicine for users of ASL, there was also mention of how the medical field views cochlear implants nearly solely, possibly understandably so, as a device to fix an issue. While this may be one perspective on the issue, making sure everyone involved in the decision-making process has a full understanding on what having a cochlear implant means for the user, the deaf community, and others closely involved is an important step in the process.%0a%0aA second consideration with the cochlear implant is equal distribution among those who wish to have one. In data from the US and UK about implants, there was evidence to suggest that the distribution and use of cochlear implants is not equal and that socioeconomic standing and race can play a role. Health insurance differences could also significantly affect this situation. Unequal distribution could potentially exacerbate existing issues with socioeconomic divisions in society. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://academic.oup.com/jdsde/article/11/1/102/410842%0ahttps://www-jstor-org.cmu.idm.oclc.org/stable/pdf/3528774.pdf?%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Expansion: Two Considerations on Cochlear Implants%0a:Author: VikramM%0a:Original: [[Articles.CochlearImplants|CochlearImplants]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.sathyas|sathyas]]%0a:Section: A%0a:Completed: 05.05.2021 - 22:02%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhile researching for the linguistic discrimination in the wild category, I came across discussion of the bias in the medical field in favor of cochlear implants. In the discussion about discrimination in medicine for users of ASL, there was also mention of how the medical field views cochlear implants nearly solely, possibly understandably so, as a device to fix an issue. While this may be one perspective on the issue, making sure everyone involved in the decision-making process has a full understanding on what having a cochlear implant means for the user, the deaf community, and others closely involved is an important step in the process.%0a%0aA second consideration with the cochlear implant is equal distribution among those who wish to have one. In data from the US and UK about implants, there was evidence to suggest that the distribution and use of cochlear implants is not equal and that socioeconomic standing and race can play a role. Health insurance differences could also significantly affect this situation. Unequal distribution could potentially exacerbate existing issues with socioeconomic divisions in society. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://academic.oup.com/jdsde/article/11/1/102/410842%0ahttps://www-jstor-org.cmu.idm.oclc.org/stable/pdf/3528774.pdf?%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_audrey:)
